=== Thunder-god's weapon ===
The name of Perkʷunos' weapon ''*meld-n-'' is attested by a group of [[cognates]] alternatively denoting 'hammer' or 'lightning' in the following traditions:

*[[Proto-Indo-European language|PIE]]: {{lang|ine-x-proto|melh₂-}}, 'to grind',{{sfn|Koch|2020|pp=142–144}}
**Northern PIE: {{lang|ine-x-proto|mel-d-(n)-}}, 'thunder-god's hammer > lightning',{{Sfn|Watkins|1995|p=429}}{{Sfn|Derksen|2015|p=544}}{{sfn|Koch|2020|pp=142–144}}
**',{{Sfn|Watkins|1995|p=429}}{{Sfn|Derksen|2015|p=544}}{{sfn|Koch|2020|pp=142–144}}
***[[Proto-Germanic language|Germanic]]: {{lang|gem-x-proto|melðunija}},{{Sfn|Watkins|1995|p=429}}{{Sfn|West|2007|p=253–254}}
****[[Old Norse]]: ''[[Mjölnir|mjǫllnir]]'', the hammer of [[Thor]]; cf. also ''myln'', 'fire',{{Sfn|Derksen|2008|p=333}}{{Sfn|West|2007|p=253–254}}
***[[Proto-Balto-Slavic language|Balto-Slavic]]: ''*mild-n-'',{{Sfn|Derksen|2008|p=333}}
****[[Proto-Slavic|Slavic]]: *''mlъldni'',{{Sfn|Derksen|2008|p=333}}
*****[[Old Church Slavonic]]: ''mlъni'' or ''mlъnii'', [[Serbo-Croatian]]: ''múnja'' (муња), [[Slovene language|Slovene]] ''mółnja'',{{Sfn|Derksen|2008|p=333}} [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]: ''{{lang|bg|мълния}}'',<ref name=":1">Rhys, John. ''Lectures on the origin and growth of religion as illustrated by Celtic heathendom''. London, Edinburgh [etc.]: Williams and Norgate. 1892. p. 59.</ref> [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]]: ''молња'', 'lightning',<ref>Australian National University. ''Routledge Macedonian-English Dictionary''. Routledge. 1998. p. 263. {{ISBN|0-415-16046-4}}</ref>
*****[[Russian language|Russian]]: ''mólnija'' (молния), 'lightning', [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] ''maladnjá'' (<small>[[Dialect|dial]].</small>) 'lightning without thunder',{{Sfn|Derksen|2008|p=333}} [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]]: ''маланка'', 'lightning',<ref name=":1" />
*****[[Czech language|Czech]]: {{lang|cs|mlna}} (<small>[[Archaic (linguistics)|arch]].</small>), [[Polish language|Polish]] {{lang|pl|mełnia}} (<small>dial.</small>),{{Sfn|Derksen|2008|p=333}} [[Sorbian languages|Lusatian]]: ''milina'' (<small>arch.</small>) 'lightning' (<small>modern</small> 'electricity'),<ref>Raede, John W. "The Linguistic Importance of Lusatian." Canadian Slavonic Papers / Revue Canadienne Des Slavistes 9, no. 2 (1967): 231-44. http://www.jstor.org/stable/40866134.</ref><ref>Афанасьев, А.Н. ''Поэтические воззрения славян на природу: Опыт сравнительного изучения славянских преданий и верований в связи с мифическими сказаниями других родственных народов''. Том 1. Moskva: Izd. K. Soldatenkova 1865. p. 253. (In Russian) [https://archive.org/details/poeticheskiiavoz01afan/page/254/mode/2up]</ref><ref>Raede, John W. "Upper Lusatian Synonyms, A Language-Building Element." Canadian Slavonic Papers / Revue Canadienne Des Slavistes 11, no. 2 (1969): 221-35. http://www.jstor.org/stable/40866229.</ref>
****[[Proto-Baltic language|Baltic]]: ''*mildnā'',{{Sfn|Watkins|1995|p=429}}
*****[[Old Prussian language|Old Prussian]]: {{lang|prg|mealde}}, 'lightning bolt',{{Sfn|Derksen|2015|p=544}}
*****[[Latvian language|Latvian]]: ''milna'', the 'hammer of the Thunderer', [[Perkūnas|Pērkōns]],{{Sfn|Derksen|2015|p=544}}
***[[Proto-Celtic language|Celtic]]: *''meldo''-,{{sfn|Koch|2020|pp=142–144}} 
****[[Gaulish]]: ''Meldos'', an epithet of thunder divinity [[Loucetios]];<ref>{{cite book|last=Koch|first=John T.|title=Celtic Culture: A Historical Encyclopedia|date=2006|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=1-85109-440-7|page=1209|author-link=John T. Koch}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Rolland |first=Henri |date=1944 |title=Inscriptions antiques de Glanum [Saint- Rémy-de-Provence] (Bouches-du-Rhône) |url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/galia_0016-4119_1944_num_2_1_1989 |journal=Gallia |volume=2 |issue=1 |pages=167–223 |doi=10.3406/galia.1944.1989}}</ref> as well as ''Meldi'' (*''Meldoi''), a tribal name, and ''Meldio'', a personal name.{{sfn|Koch|2020|pp=142–144}}
****[[Welsh language|Welsh]]: {{lang|cy|mellt}}, 'lightning, thunderbolts' ([[Singulative number|<small>sing.</small>]] {{lang|cy|mellten}}, 'bolt of lightning'), and ''Mabon am Melld'' or ''Mabon fab Mellt'' ('Mabon son of Mellt'),{{Sfn|Watkins|1995|p=429}}{{sfn|Koch|2020|pp=142–144}}
****[[Breton language|Breton]]: ''mell'', 'hammer',{{Sfn|West|2007|p=253–254}}{{Sfn|Le Quellec|1996|p=291}}
****[[Middle Irish]]: ''mell'', 'rounded summit, small hill', possibly via semantic contamination from {{lang|mis|*ferkunyā}}, '(wooded) mountains'.{{Sfn|Le Quellec|1996|p=291}}

Another PIE term derived from the verbal root {{lang|mis|*melh₂-}} ('to grind'), {{lang|mis|*molh₁-tlo-}} ('grinding device'), also served as a common word for 'hammer', as in Old Church Slavonic ''mlatъ'', Latin {{lang|la|malleus}}, and Hittite {{lang|hit|malatt}} ('sledgehammer, bludgeon').{{sfn|Koch|2020|pp=142–144}}

19th-century scholar [[Francis Hindes Groome]] cited the existence of the [[Romani language|Romani]] word ''malúna'' as a loanword from Slavic ''molnija''.<ref>Groome, Francis Hindes. ''In Gipsy tents''. Edinburgh: W. P. Nimmo & co.. 1890. p. 12. [https://archive.org/details/ingipsytents00groogoog/page/n26/mode/2up?q=thunder]</ref> The [[Komi language|Komi]] word ''molńi'' or ''molńij'' ('lightning') has also been borrowed from Slavic.<ref>Alves, Victor Hugo Sampaio. "As Direções em que Thor Arremessou sua Arma: Apontamentos Sobre a Etimologia e os Paralelos Mitológicos de Mjölnir". In: NEARCO (Núcleo de Estudos da Antiguidade-NEA da Universidade do Estado do Rio de Janeiro): Revista Eletrônica de Antiguidade 2020, Volume XII, Número I. p. 190. {{ISSN|1982-8713}} (in Portuguese)</ref>

