*[[Paleo-Balkan languages|Paleo-Balkanic]]:
**[[Albanian language|Albanian]]:
***[[Perëndi]] "god, deity, sky", considered by some scholars to be an Albanian sky and thunder god (from ''per-en-'', an extension of [[Proto-Indo-European language|PIE]] {{lang|ine-x-proto|per-}}, 'to strike', attached to ''-di'', the sky-god [[Dyeus|Dyēus]], thus related to ''*per-uhₓn-os'' (see above); although the Albanian ''perëndoj'', 'to set (of the sun)', from Latin ''parentare'', 'a sacrifice (to the dead), to satisfy', has also been proposed as the origin of the theonym,<ref name="West 2007 242–244">{{harvnb|West|2007|pp=242–244}}; {{harvnb|Mallory|Adams|1997|pp=582–583}}; {{harvnb|Jakobson|1985|pp=6, 19–21}}; {{harvnb|Treimer|1971|pp=31–33}}.</ref>{{Sfn|Orel|1998|pp=315–316}}
**[[Greek mythology|Greek]]: {{transliteration|grc|keraunos}} (κεραυνός), the name of [[Zeus]]'s thunderbolt, which was sometimes also deified (by [[Metathesis (linguistics)|metathesis]] of *{{transliteration|grc|per(k)aunos}}; although the root *''ḱerh₂-'', 'shatter, smash' has also been proposed),{{Sfn|West|2007|p=243}}{{Sfn|Beekes|2009|p=677}} and the ''Herkyna'' spring-nymph, associated with a river of the same name and identified with [[Demeter]] (the name could be a borrowing as it rather follows Celtic sound laws),{{Sfn|York|1993|p=240}}{{Sfn|West|2007|p=243}}
**[[Thracian religion|Thracian]]: Perkos/Perkon (Περκος/Περκων),<ref>Georgiev, Vladimir I.. "Thrakisch und Dakisch". Band 29/2. Teilband Sprache und Literatur (Sprachen und Schriften [Forts.]), edited by Wolfgang Haase, Berlin, Boston: De Gruyter, 1983. p. 1209. {{doi|10.1515/9783110847031-016}}</ref> a [[Thracian horseman|horseman hero]] depicted as facing a tree surrounded by a snake.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Toporov |first=V. |author-link=Vladimir Toporov |title=The Thracian Horseman in an Indo-European Perspective |url=https://www.ceeol.com/search/article-detail?id=772269 |journal=ORPHEUS. Journal of Indo-European and Thracian Studies |volume=18 |date=1990 |pages=46–63 [57]}}</ref>{{Sfn|Jackson|2002|p=75–76}}{{Sfn|West|2007|p=243}}{{sfn|Lajoye|Oudaer|2014|p=51}} His name is also attested as Ήρω Περκω and Περκώνει "in Odessos and the vicinities".<ref>Beševliev, Veselin. "[https://ojs.lib.uom.gr/index.php/BalkanStudies/article/view/2295 Vorthrakisch?]". In: ''Balkan Studies'' Vol 31, No 1 (1990): 48.</ref><ref>{{interlanguage link|Popov, Dimitar|bg|Димитър Попов (историк)}}. "[https://www.ceeol.com/search/article-detail?id=871733 Le Dieu Supreme des Thraces. Incarnations et Identifications, Traductions - Notations et Noms - Appellations]" [The Supreme God of Thracians. Incarnations and Identifications, Translations - Remarks and Names - Appellations]. In ''Thracia'' 18 (2009): 28-30.</ref>
